  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Hermit's Dwelling
  author: Park Eun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I question Heaven about all things, then laugh at myself alone.
    This heart of mine finds no accord with the world's way.
    By chance, beneath the bright moon, I sought you out for talk—
    and deep wine's solace came to comfort all my sorrows.

    To drift through the year in leisure brings a joy that suffices,
    and for my humble state in common times, why blame anyone?
    Already drunk, I drink the deeper for the chrysanthemum flowers,
    and though I mean to leave, still linger for a verse well-made.
  footnotes:
    - The chrysanthemum (황화, 黃花) symbolizes solitary refinement and resilience in the face of life's hardships in East Asian poetic tradition.
    - The hermetic tone and theme of withdrawing from worldly affairs while finding joy in simple pleasures suggests a Daoist or Buddhist influence common in Korean literati poetry.
